Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms (DRESS)

Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE): 
      SLE can manifest with all the symptoms listed. Autoimmune hemolysis refers to the destruction of red blood cells by antibodies produced in lupus.

Evans Syndrome:  
      Characterized by AIHA and ITP. Symptoms are fever, hemolysis, petechiae, mucosal ulcerations, and maculopapular rash. ITP may cause seizures, but not AIHA.

Mixed cryoglobulinemia: 
      A type III hypersensitivity reaction caused by immune complexes that precipitate at cold temperatures. Can manifest with autoimmune hemolysis, skin rash, arthralgias, and cryoprecipitate.

(less likely)  
    Drug-induced hypersensitivity syndrome (DIHS): 
      May present with fever, rash (maculopapular or morbilliform), lymphadenopathy, and internal organ involvement.

(Less likely)  
    Acute viral infection (e.g., Epstein-Barr virus, cytomegalovirus):  
      These viruses can cause a wide range of symptoms, including autoimmune hemolysis, oral lesions, fever, rash, and seizures. The specific diagnosis is made through laboratory and imaging studies.

Other autoimmune diseases:
      Sjogrens syndrome and autoimmune cytopenias (ITP and AIHA). Each may cause only some of those listed symptoms, and may require additional testing to confirm.
